studies of the effects of social structure on economic behavior siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project studies of the effects of social structure on economic behavior title studies of the effects of social structure on economic behavior principal investigator matthew jackson dates june 1 2007 may 31 2010 sponsor national science foundation the network structure of relationships underlies a number of social economic and political interactions who we know affects our behavior and well being in many ways including which jobs we find which products we buy what our political opinions are even whether or not we engage in criminal activities among many other things beyond network structures playing a role in behavior it is also well documented that there is a strong tendency for people to interact with other people who are similar to themselves this is known as homophily and has been documented in terms of ethnicity gender political affiliation age religion profession and a variety of other socio economic categories in addition there is evidence that interaction patters differ depending on group size eg minority groups are more likely to interact with each other this project involves developing models to provide theoretical predictions concerning social network formation in the presence of a diversity of types of individuals as well as modeling the diffusion of behavior on networks that exhibit segregation stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
